{"word":"vessel","entries":[{"language":{"code":"en","name":"English"},"partOfSpeech":"noun","pronunciations":[{"type":"ipa","text":"/ˈvɛsəl/","tags":["General American","Received Pronunciation"]},{"type":"ipa","text":"[ˈvɛsɫ̩]","tags":["General American","Received Pronunciation"]},{"type":"ipa","text":"/ˈvesəl/","tags":["General Australian","New Zealand"]}],"forms":[{"word":"vessels","tags":["plural"]},{"word":"vessell","tags":["alternative","obsolete"]}],"senses":[{"definition":"A craft for transportation on or in water, air, or space.","tags":[],"examples":[],"quotes":[],"synonyms":[],"antonyms":[],"subsenses":[{"definition":"(nautical) Any craft designed for transportation on or in water, such as a ship, boat, or submarine.","tags":[],"examples":[],"quotes":[{"text":"But my hope was, that if I stood along this coast till I came to that part where the English traded, I should find some of their vessels upon their usual design of trade, that would relieve and take us in.","reference":"1719 May 6 (Gregorian calendar), [Daniel Defoe], The Life and Strange Surprizing Adventures of Robinson Crusoe, […], London: […] W[illiam] Taylor […], →OCLC:"},{"text":"Merchants, common sailors, captains of vessels, skippers, […] naval officers of all countries, and the Governments of several states on the two continents, were deeply interested in the matter.","reference":"1873, Jules Verne, chapter I, in [anonymous], transl., Twenty Thousand Leagues under the Seas; […], James R. Osgood edition, Boston, Mass.: Geo[rge] M[urray] Smith & Co., →OCLC, part I, page 3:"},{"text":"He saw now clearly that the sole crew of the vessel was these two dead men, and though he could not see their faces, he saw by their outstretched hands, which were all of ragged flesh, that they had been subjected to some strange exceptional process of decay.","reference":"1905, H. G. Wells, The Empire of the Ants:"},{"text":"Conditions were horrendous aboard most British naval vessels at the time. Scurvy and other diseases ran rampant, killing more seamen each year than all other causes combined, including combat.","reference":"2012 March 25, William E. Carter, Merri Sue Carter, “The British Longitude Act Reconsidered”, in American Scientist, volume 100, number 2, page 87:"}],"synonyms":["watercraft"],"antonyms":[],"translations":[{"language":{"code":"sq","name":"Albanian"},"word":"anë"},{"language":{"code":"ar","name":"Arabic"},"word":"فُلْك"},{"language":{"code":"az","name":"Azerbaijani"},"word":"gəmi"},{"language":{"code":"be","name":"Belarusian"},"word":"судзі́на"},{"language":{"code":"be","name":"Belarusian"},"word":"су́дзіна"},{"language":{"code":"be","name":"Belarusian"},"word":"су́дна"},{"language":{"code":"be","name":"Belarusian"},"word":"карабе́ль"},{"language":{"code":"bg","name":"Bulgarian"},"word":"плава́телен съд"},{"language":{"code":"bg","name":"Bulgarian"},"word":"ко́раб"},{"language":{"code":"my","name":"Burmese"},"word":"သင်္ဘော"},{"language":{"code":"ca","name":"Catalan"},"word":"vaixell"},{"language":{"code":"cmn","name":"Chinese Mandarin"},"word":"船隻 /船只"},{"language":{"code":"cmn","name":"Chinese Mandarin"},"word":"船"},{"language":{"code":"cs","name":"Czech"},"word":"loď"},{"language":{"code":"cs","name":"Czech"},"word":"plavidlo"},{"language":{"code":"da","name":"Danish"},"word":"fartøj"},{"language":{"code":"nl","name":"Dutch"},"word":"vaartuig"},{"language":{"code":"fo","name":"Faroese"},"word":"far"},{"language":{"code":"fi","name":"Finnish"},"word":"alus"},{"language":{"code":"fr","name":"French"},"word":"vaisseau"},{"language":{"code":"fy","name":"West-Frisian"},"word":"doaze"},{"language":{"code":"gl","name":"Galician"},"word":"navío"},{"language":{"code":"ka","name":"Georgian"},"word":"ხომალდი"},{"language":{"code":"ka","name":"Georgian"},"word":"გემი"},{"language":{"code":"de","name":"German"},"word":"Schiff"},{"language":{"code":"de","name":"German"},"word":"Boot"},{"language":{"code":"de","name":"German"},"word":"Wasserfahrzeug"},{"languag