me, to beare my Name before the Gentiles, and Kings, and the children of Israel.","reference":"1611, The Holy Bible, […] (King James Version), London: […] Robert Barker, […], →OCLC, Acts 9:15:"},{"text":"[The serpent] fit vessel, fittest imp of fraud, in whom to enter.","reference":"1667, John Milton, “Book VIII”, in Paradise Lost. […], London: […] [Samuel Simmons], and are to be sold by Peter Parker […]; [a]nd by Robert Boulter […]; [a]nd Matthias Walker, […], →OCLC; republished as Paradise Lost in Ten Books: […], London: Basil Montagu Pickering […], 1873, →OCLC:"},{"text":"I am a vessel that’s empty and useless / I am a bad seed that fell by the way","reference":"1975, Dolly Parton, “The Seeker”:"},{"text":"But they [Christian nationalists] excuse all that by saying God works in mysterious ways, and that he sent us this flawed vessel by which we can achieve the goals that we want to achieve.","reference":"2024 February 29, Tim Jonze, quoting Rob Reiner, “‘We need to reach as many people as we can’: Rob Reiner on Trump, family – and his brilliant, beloved movies”, in The Guardian, →ISSN:"}],"synonyms":[],"antonyms":[],"subsenses":[]},{"definition":"(biology) A tube or canal that carries fluid in an animal or plant.","tags":[],"examples":["Blood and lymph vessels are found in humans; xylem and phloem vessels are found in plants."],"quotes":[],"synonyms":[],"antonyms":[],"subsenses":[]}],"synonyms":["vessel"],"antonyms":[]},{"language":{"code":"en","name":"English"},"partOfSpeech":"verb","pronunciations":[{"type":"ipa","text":"/ˈvɛsəl/","tags":["General American","Received Pronunciation"]},{"type":"ipa","text":"[ˈvɛsɫ̩]","tags":["General American","Received Pronunciation"]},{"type":"ipa","text":"/ˈvesəl/","tags":["General Australian","New Zealand"]}],"forms":[{"word":"vessels","tags":["present","singular","third-person"]},{"word":"vesseling","tags":["US","participle","present"]},{"word":"vesselling","tags":["UK","participle","present"]},{"word":"vesseled","tags":["US","participle","past"]},{"word":"vesseled","tags":["US","past"]},{"word":"vesselled","tags":["UK","participle","past"]},{"word":"vesselled","tags":["UK","past"]},{"word":"vessell","tags":["alternative","obsolete"]}],"senses":[{"definition":"(transitive) To put into a vessel.","tags":["transitive"],"examples":["1577, William Harrison, The Description of England in Holinshed’s Chronicles, Volume 1, Book 3, Chapter 12 “Of venemous beastes &c.,”\nOur hony alſo is taken and reputed to be the beſt bycauſe it is harder, better wrought & clenlyer veſſelled vp, thẽ that which cõmeth from beyond the ſea, where they ſtampe and ſtraine their combes, Bées, & young Blow|inges altogither into the ſtuffe, as I haue béene informed.","1627, Francis Bacon, Sylva Sylvarum: or, A Naturall Historie, London: W. Lee, Cent. VI, section 529, p. 137,\nThe fourth Rule ſhall be, to marke what Herbs, ſome Earths doe put fourth of themſelves; And to take that Earth, and to Pot it, or to Veſſell it; And in that to ſet the Seed you would change […]","[Samuel 'Sam' Oliver:] Alright (or: All right), so the Devil didn't say that the winner was the one who vesseled (or: vesselled) him, just the one who sends him back to hell."],"quotes":[{"text":"Man had at the firſt, and ſo have all ſouls before their entrance into the body, an explicite methodicall knowledge, but they are no ſooner veſſel’d, but that liberty is loſt, and nothing remains but a vaſt confuſed notion of the creature […]","reference":"1662, John Heydon, The Harmony of the World, London: Robert Horn, Epistle Dedicatory:"}],"synonyms":[],"antonyms":[],"subsenses":[]}],"synonyms":[],"antonyms":[]}],"source":{"url":"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/vessel","license":{"name":"CC BY-SA 4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/"}}}